Lab 2. Custom UNIX-based commands


Custom commands in the Unix terminal are user-defined shortcuts or scripts that perform specific tasks. They enhance productivity by automating repetitive actions or combining multiple commands into one.

We are going to create a custom command that will display system information using existing UNIX-based commands.

Create file with command:

sudo nano /usr/local/bin/system_info

And paste the following code:

echo Hostname: DESKTOP-4JPUDVN
echo Current User: syimykr
echo Disk Space: Filesystem Size Used Avail Use% Mounted on /dev/sdd 1007G 1.3G 955G 1% / rootfs 1.8G 2.7M 1.8G 1% /init none 1.8G 0 1.8G 0% /dev/shm none 1.8G 556K 1.8G 1% /run none 1.8G 0 1.8G 0% /run/lock none 1.8G 76K 1.8G 1% /run/user drivers 477G 264G 213G 56% /usr/lib/wsl/drivers none 1.8G 0 1.8G 0% /usr/lib/wsl/lib none 1.8G 4.0K 1.8G 1% /mnt/wsl none 1.8G 76K 1.8G 1% /mnt/wslg/versions.txt none 1.8G 76K 1.8G 1% /mnt/wslg/doc none 1.8G 0 1.8G 0% /usr/lib/modules/6.6.87.2-microsoft-standard-WSL2 C:\ 477G 264G 213G 56% /mnt/c tmpfs 360M 20K 360M 1% /run/user/1000 tmpfs 360M 20K 360M 1% /run/user/0


Make it executable:

sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/system_info

Test it:

system_info



Following these principles you should create 4 small study projects. The following UNIX commands are preferred to know in prior:

date, echo, cp, ls, mkdir, whoami, rm, mv, top, dh

If you struggle with writing reliable scripts, please don’t hesitate to google and understand commands that you might need!

 Create a script to display a greeting

Write a shell script named greet.sh that:
Outputs a greeting message, e.g., Hello, [username]!

Create a script that displays time remaining before work day ends

Write a shell script named current_time.sh that:
Displays the current time and time remaining before work day ends.
E.g. Current time: 13:30. Work day ends after 4 hours and 30 minutes.



Create a script to count word occurrences in a file

Write a shell script named count_word.sh that:
Takes two arguments: a file name and a word to search for.
Counts and displays how many times the specified word appears in the file.


Create a Script to find and delete empty files

Write a shell script named delete_empty_files.sh that:
Takes a directory as an argument.
Finds all empty files in that directory and deletes them.
The script should print the names of deleted files.



syimykr@DESKTOP-4JPUDVN:~$ ./count_words.sh word_file.txt create
The word 'create' appears 2 times in 'word_file.txt'.
syimykr@DESKTOP-4JPUDVN:~$ ./count_words.sh word_file.txt Create
The word 'Create' appears 5 times in 'word_file.txt'.
syimykr@DESKTOP-4JPUDVN:~$ nano delete_empty_files.sh
syimykr@DESKTOP-4JPUDVN:~$ nano count_words.sh
syimykr@DESKTOP-4JPUDVN:~$ nano delete_empty_files.sh
